/code-relay\n\n### 2. **Beads** - Persistent Memory for AI Programming\n- **Published:** February 4, 2026\n- Created by Steve Yegge to give AI coding agents persistent memory\n- A Git-based task management system designed specifically for AI to read\n- Stores detailed tasks in JSON format within your repository\n- Helps AI remember progress across multiple days\n- GitHub: https://github.com/steveyegge/beads\n\n### 3. **mono** - Memory Exoskeleton for Claude Code\n- **Published:** January 28, 2026\n- A memory system designed for Claude Code\n- Uses markdown files and Git workflows to capture insights, decisions, and context\n- Creates a `memory` folder in project root with timestamped markdown files\n- Provides 20+ slash commands for automation\n- Self-bootstrapping tool (developed with Claude and used to develop itself)\n\n### 4. **aivectormemory** - Personal AI Memory Bank\n- **Published:** February 15, 2026\n- Creates a private AI memory library\n- Stores preferences (e.g., \"all frontend projects use Tailwind CSS + TypeScript strict mode\")\n- AI automatically retrieves memories for subsequent requests\n- Addresses the \"last 100 meters\" problem of general model personalization\n\n### 5. **OpenClaw/Clawdbot** - Local AI Agent with Permanent Memory\n- **Published:** February 6, 2026\n- Implements \"mandatory recall\" with `memory_search` tool\n- Uses semantic search across MEMORY.md and memory/*.md files\n- Features dual-layer memory storage system\n- Allows manual editing of memory files with automatic reindexing\n\n## 📌 Key Trends\n\nAll of these systems address a common challenge: **AI coding assistants losing context between sessions**. The solutions generally fall into three approaches:\n\n1. **File-based memory** (markdown/JSON in repository)\n2. **Semantic search** over memory files\n3. **Git-integrated workflows** for version control\n\nWould you like me to search for more specific information about any of these projects or explore particular aspects of AI workspace memory systems?\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
